We owned the original Sonicare for years and we loved it.  When we bought this model, we expected the same good performance we had from the original.  We were sorely disappointed by the fact that the screw on brush heads were flimsy and didn't screw down on the base unit securely.  We found the transfer of the ultra-sonic vibrations were dampened by the fact that the brush heads didn't remain tightly connected to the base unit.  After using this model for a year, we were receiving negative feedback from our dental hygienist.  We ended up buying another brand of electronic toothbrush but still weren't getting the results we expected.  Finally bought the Sonicare Flexcare model with snap on style heads.  This model works beautifully.  I would recommend you NOT buy Sonicare products with screw on style brush heads as they continuously loosen themselves from the base unit which degrades their performance.  The snap on style heads available on some Sonicare models remain securely attached to the base unit and therefore, transfer the ultrasonic vibrations to the brush head and your teeth more effectively.

The first six months where great, only needed to replace the bag once. However this vacuum lost its power switch yesterday. Turned it on and started cleaning up, and when time to turn it off the switch would not work! try and try and the thing would not turn off. So I unplugged it from the wall. The reason this is a big deal is when someone pays close to 100 dollars for a product it should last more than six months, and the other reason is when I plug it back in or unplug it there are sparks at least half inch long coming from the outlet. This not only will hurt someone, but will make the outlet in the house no good either. As far as care goes it is well maintained. Bag change and belt (which it doesn't need one because it never worked long enough). Is this worth 90 dollars, NO. If you take the top off to look at the motor and power switch its held together by cardboard. And the switch is cheap plastic so no wonder why it quit working. Checked to see if there is a replacement switch, and guess what, Eureka has discontinued the belts and Bags, and no power switch.  So to bring this to a end, the 20ft power cord is short, the bag beings to smell after while, all plastic, switch fails, all this thing has for it is power. Save the money and buy the cheaper Bissell and Hoover bagged uprights. For the money they offer more.

I purchased this at home depot based on the overwhelmingly positive reviews on Amazon to repair my headlight mounting brackets.nnI cleaned the surface using alcohol and some paper towels. Next, I mixed the two parts equally (50/50) and attempted to apply a very generous amount of the material onto the surface of the broken parts and set it in position. Now the grey stuff smelled like diarrhea. I'm not even trying to be funny here, it really smells THAT BAD. If you're trying this stuff out, USE IT OUTDOORS OR IN YOUR GARAGE. Where ever you use it, make sure you have plenty of ventilation cause this stuff will stink up the place.nnThe next day, I began mounting the headlights back onto my car. Needless to say, both brackets broke when I wasn't even applying much pressure. Not sure if what I got was a dud but this is surely unacceptable. The conditions in which the epoxy was mixed was in doors and humidity was low.

I know you get what you pay for, but this was way below that standard. I would have sent it back, but I was pressed for time and I needed this style of tool to finish working on our pinewood derby cars.

I purchased these to test a circuit. Instead of quality test leads I received junk! Non of the wire ends where crimped or soldered to the test clips! All they did was strip the end of the wire, bend over the exposed wire and push it into the barely crimped test clip ends! And the wire is SO fine a gauge that any kind of current through it produces high resistance! Between the high resistance and not making contact with the test clips these are a total FAIL! I had to buy decent wire and solder/crimp the ends to get them working. There is also no rating on wire or test clips plastic boots! DO NOT USE FOR AC OR HIGH VOLTAGE! So if you buy this you can pretty much toss everything except the test clips! Very expensive test clips!! A better avenue would be to buy a bulk box of clips, wire, and build the cables yourself! Very displeased!

I didn't read the reviews before buying and was disappointed to find two major issues:nn1)The plastic clip covers are so slippery that I can't really use them without removing the covers completely.n2)The gauge is so tiny that even the short length barely over 1 foot results in .8 ohms of resistance. Absolutely useless for anything that needs to carry any current (even 1 amp and your voltage is already 1.6 V less than is was at the source by the time you lose .8 V on each end). For resistance measurement they add a total of 1.6 ohms to the total measurement if used to connect something to the meter. They are only good for measuring voltage with the tiny measurement current that a meter uses for that. If you use them anywhere else in a circuit keep in mind that you just added a .8 ohm resistor whether you wanted one or not.nnConclusion: not worth the cheap price. Buy some clips without the wires and crimp / solder them to your own quality wire.

This shop vac could be decent, unfortunately there is no appropriate bag designed for this vacuum. The problem is that any bag that actually fits this unit is designed for low-rise vacuums, not this tall type. The result is those wrap-around bags cant expand because the motor is in the center preventing any degree of expansion to retain debris. The other problem is that there is no bag actually designed to reach the bottom of the vacuum, so that as the bag fills up, it ends up hanging on the inlet causing pressure on the paper and eventually ripping open blowing all the debrisdust all over the place. Those disposable wrap around paper filters that go over the foam sleeve clog up way too fast. Another problem is that housing just below the motor that is supposed to hold the foam sleeve directly interferes with the inlet leaving no room even if there was a tall bag that could reach the bottom of the vacuum offering support as debris collects and not putting pressure on the bag opening. Very poor design. To me, this was a waste of money.

For my V6 GT I've been using the stock CM thermal compound.  Temps got up to 80C or so at 4.6GHz @ 1.3V on my 2500K.  80C is a high limit for Ivy and Sandy Bridge, so I was interested in getting the 5-10C drops other people are getting.  The result:  10C HIGHER temps at idle and 3C HIGHER temps at load.  I know AS5 has a LONG cure time, so I hope I can give it a better review after it cures.  It's supposed to cure in 100Hrs or so, but review websites are finding it's more like 120Hrs+.  Still, the stock thermal compound from CM has NO cure time, which makes it more valuable to me.  If performance doesn't improve over the next week, I'll try reapplying and see where that gets me.

You've got to be kidding me! I've purchased similarly bottled super-glue from a local hobby shop. This product does not compare to anything they sell. This Gap Filling glue is a failure. It will not cure within any reasonable time fame. My Gap Filling hobby shop glue certainly cured slower in order to flow into recessed nooks and crannies. It gave you a little time to manipulate things, if needed. But this stuff...Wow! You'd better be prepared to wait a while for anything to START to happen! Even with an applied hardener, the process was slow and questionably secure when cured.nnThe only conclusion I can come to is that this formula, and possibly the whole Bob Smith line, has been deliberately reduced in its adhesive composition in order to either: 1) reduce the price or, 2) to reduce inexperienced people's exposure to the foibles of the main-line product. Whether Bob Smith is a re-bottler or the original mfg., I don't know. However, I do know that this product is not what it should be...for my use, anyway.

This is a nice set of sheet metal pieces of different thickness. I used them as shims for stainless steel poles, shims like this were invaluable to bring the poles to vertical position within 0.2 degrees. However, be aware that it is tempered steel. It is extremely hard and brittle, the kind of steel that is used to make blades and scrapers. It is very hard to card. I started with small tin snips - no luck, just would not bite into it. Then, I used a jig saw with a Bosch blade for metal. The blade survived about an inch length of cut before becoming ultimately dull. I cut a few small shims with a hack saw, then went to a store and bought quite massive snips with dual lever action which ultimately enabled it to cut these pieces into smaller shims - but with a lot of effort, surprising for such thin material. I would very much prefer a regular, softer steel. But this was the only set that I could find.nnI also was hoping to make holes in it using a hole punch, but this also failed. The thin tempered steel was harder than the punch dies.nnGood quality set, but very hard to work with. Not sure what the target buyers are.

The Paladin 1543 ProNavigator does a good job testing CAT5 LAN cables. A great plus is its capability to test a cross-over fault between twisted pairs of wires. When I began testing 2 and 4-conductor telephone cables terminated with RJ11 or RJ14 jacks, I found to my surprise that all of the commercially-produced patch cables had the jack wiring reversed so that pin 3 on jack #1 was connected to pin 4 on jack #2, and pin 2 on jack #1 was connected to pin 5 on jack #2. This shows up as a CROSS on the Paladin. If anyone knows why this seems to be the manufacturing standard, please post it in the Comments section of this review. My guess is they do it that way because it is cheaper to not have to turn the flat cable over before attaching the second jack.

I recently engaged in a nutrition and workout program with an aim a reducing body fat and gaining muscle.  The best way to know if you are making progress is by monitoring your body fat.  While there are many expensive methods for determining your body fat, utilization of calibers are the cheapest method with some level of accuracy.  The important part is to make sure you use them in a consistent fashion (location of the fold on the body, position of the caliper jaws on the skin, and time frame after releasing the jaws to take the reading) when measuring the skin fold.nnThe Slim Guide Skin Fold Calipers work as advertised and expected.  Just press the trigger which opens the jaws then place the calipers in position and release the trigger.  The spring will provide the appropriate force while you read the measurement.  Some measurements will require the use of another person (like triceps and back) to perform the measurements.  The small numbers can be hard to read if you are doing the measurement yourself.nnThe calipers are made of plastic but appear to be pretty durable (I dropped them a couple of times on the tile floor while taking measurements).nnOverall, and excellent product and does the job, just wish the numbers were a little bigger.

Note - I'm putting the bulk of this review on the 3D TerraLUX conversion as well, as I purchased that kit, too.nnI've had my 4D Maglite for over 10 years, and I've always considered it to be a good, but not great flashlight.  I have a couple tactical Surefire flashlights and a Pelican flashlight that I use as a firefighter that are all MUCH brighter than even the best Maglite.  However, the Surefires were both over $100 each, and they both use very expensive lithium CR123A batteries that do not last very long, which is a major drawback.  The Pelican was also extremely expensive, but it was purpose-built for firefighting and HAZMAT incidents.  It has decent battery life, and it does use standard C batteries, which is nice.nnSo, taking all that into account, I rarely use the Surefires except for tactical purposes, and I use the Pelican when I need a bright flashlight.  When I need a standard issue, not very expensive flashlight for general purposes, I grab one of my 4 Maglites, and if I need the flashlight to be on for a while, I grab the 4D one.nnI recently had an opportunity to mess around with one of the 2D Maglite LED flashlights.  From things I've seen on the internet, it was a 3rd Generation LED, with a square green base supporting the actual LED and a rating of 134 lumens.  This thing was a GREAT flashlight.  I was utterly stunned at the brightness of the light and the distance at which I could clearly see objects illuminated (250 yards plus).  This thing was brighter than my Surefires with brand new batteries.  I was also amazed at how well I could focus the beam, and how concentrated it stayed, even at great distances (something I cannot do with my Surefires).nnSo, I decided to see if I could find a conversion kit to change my current crop of Maglites over to the much brighter LED format.  These TerraLUX kits seemed to be the only real option.  They make multiple sizes to cover all my various Maglites - 2AA, 2D, 3D, 4D (Yes, I have a flashlight problem), and they had pretty good ratings and reviews on Amazon.nnAs soon as I got them I switched out my standard bulbs for the LEDs.  The switch couldn't have been any easier - Just unscrew the lens, unscrew a collar, pull out the old bulb and put in the LED.  No problems at all with installation.  I turned the flashlight on and I was pretty impressed with the improved brightness over the standard bulb.  It was DEFINITELY brighter, no doubt about it.  However, when compared to the 2D factory-made Maglite LED flashlight, it was noticeably not as bright, and it was not as bright as my Surefires, either.  The distance at which object were clearly illuminated was probably 150 yards - nothing to be disappointed with, but not nearly the distance of the factory Maglite LED.  I was really hoping that the TerraLUX conversion and the factory Maglite LED would be exactly the same, but unfortunately, they are not.  There is simply no way that the advertised 140 lumens of this conversion is correct.  My utterly unscientific and know-nothing guess would be that it's maybe 100-110 lumens.nnSo, to sum up - yes, this is an improvement over the standard Maglite bulb.  It is brighter, extremely easy to install, LEDs supposedly last forever, and they greatly improve battery life.  However, if you are hoping to turn your older Maglites into something as powerful as the new Maglite LEDs, you will be disappointed.nnDo I recommend the TerraLUX conversions?  Yes.  They will take your good Maglites and put them somewhere between good and great.  But, be aware that you will not get anywhere near 140 lumens, and your friends with true Maglite LEDs will probably make fun of you for having a flashlight that is not as bright as theirs.

It has many more attachments compared to the others and its capacity is 48 oz, which allows for continuous cleaning for about 40 minutes.nnMy only beef with it is that as a professional cleaner of condos and private residences I have to carry my cleaning tools from car to house and from ground floor to first floor at each and every job. It's the one thing that is missing on an otherwise savvy investment.

Exceeded my expectations.  Using a laptop, I need all the help I can get dealing with high temps that I can.  The limited space means that upgrading the heat sink or increasing ventilation is out of the picture.  With the thermal paste that came with the computer, I would consistently overheat if the processor used its built in turbo boost, and sometimes even when the processor was limited to its default processing frequency.  This paste drastically reduced temperature buildup, so much so that I can overclock to very high levels and still keep 15-20C under my hardware's max temp, even under heavy load.  Only drawback to this product is the rather long break in period.  The manual says it requires 200 hr. to achieve full effectiveness, but it only took roughly 60 hr. for me to bring my temperature into acceptable range while overclocking both my CPU and GPU. I would strongly recommend this for anyone using a laptop for serious gaming.

My computer used to run 49 degrees to 50 degrees with the 'stock' thermal compound.  I then planned of buying a stronger processor to upgrade my laptop so I bought this arctic silver 5 3.5grams compound.  Turns out day after that the processor i'm trying to buy got sold out, in short i didn't replace my processor.  Just so i'm so bored and I told myself its useless that I bought this, i disassembled my laptop Gateway P-7805u and replaced the original thermal compound with this AS5.  And WOW, my peak temperature dropped from 50 degrees to 45 degrees, tops.  usually stays at 44 degrees.  So i would say, this pretty much made my laptop 10% cooler than my stock original thermal compound.  Needless to say, the fan doesnt run as much as it does before.  Totally worth the money!
